Nov 16 2008 	Stylish; authentic Italian	We spent just one Saturday night in the Baglioni opposite Kensington Gardens and were not disappointed. I chose this hotel as a treat for my wife as we love Italy and most things Italian. The décor is just as you see it in the photos – tasteful &amp; more simplistic than the classic baroque you might normally associate with Italian hotel design. It’s all very sophisticated, so long as you like the almost-over-the-top mix of gold, grey, mulberry and very dark wood.The service we enjoyed was almost perfect from start to finish, but lacked warmth; we found the staff to be very helpful but discreet. They would provide any assistance on request, but didn’t always take the initiative.We’d booked a deluxe room and although we arrived around noon, well before published check-in time, we were given a room and were even upgraded to a junior suite. We also asked for and were allowed a late check-out. The phrase “there’s no harm in asking” is alive and well at the Baglioni!We particularly wanted to be near to the V &amp; A museum and the location is ideal. We also walked to Knightsbridge though Kensington gardens, which took about 20 minutes, where there are some goods cafés and of course ‘Harvey Nicks’. In the evening we ate in the hotel restaurant. The meal was OK but not wonderful; the Scallop Risotto was poor value – only 2 scallops – but my Wild Boar Pappardelle was excellent. Several good wines by the glass too. Again, service was good but not exemplary. But wait – it gets better!When we returned to our room we found the room strewn with rose petals, several burning scented candles and a red rose on the bed. A lovely touch.Plusses? Modern Italian ‘boutique’ feel and décor, more personal than the large modern chain hotels, quiet, sophisticated, stylish and well located for the museum district and the Albert Hall.Minuses? Misleading brochure (yes, the terrace does overlook the park but there’s a 4-lane road in-between!). The buffet breakfast was adequate but not extensive.	
